<subSubSection id="96BC651BB7302842083AFC043B50FB70" pageId="21" pageNumber="411" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="DE193690B7302842083AFC043B50FB70" blockId="21.[94,1302,288,1307]" pageId="21" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis id="ECD2EA82B7302842083AFC043EE7FC0E" bold="true" box="[96,441,917,950]" pageId="21" pageNumber="411">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix II. Classified as Least Concern on The [UCN Red List (as C. 
<taxonomicName id="19A64D13B73028420977FC2D3EC0FC65" authorityName="Schomburgk" authorityYear="1848" box="[301,414,956,989]" class="Mammalia" family="Cebidae" genus="Cebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="21" pageNumber="411" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="olivaceus">olivaceus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="19A64D13B730284209F2FC2D3D7AFC65" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1914" box="[424,548,956,989]" class="Mammalia" family="Cebidae" genus="Cebus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="21" pageNumber="411" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brunneus">brunneus</taxonomicName>
). The Venezuelan Brown Capuchin is reported to be common. Protected areas within its distribution include Henri Pittier, El Avila, and Peninsula de Paria national parks in Venezuela, and if it is indeed the capuchin on Trinidad, very small populations are found in Bush Bush and Trinity Hills wildlife sanctuaries. Three groups totaling 31 individuals were recorded in Bush Bush and one group of twelve individuals was recorded in Trinity Hills in 1997 surveys. The population on Trinidad is classified as Critically Endangered on The IUCN Red Last.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
